1. Not all mental images are equal

There are levels:
	•	Hard render (visual certainty)
→ what you actually see
	•	Soft render (high-confidence imagination)
→ vivid memory / strong prediction
	•	Wraith mode (low-confidence projection)
→ fuzzy, grayscale, position-only

You’re operating in:

confidence-weighted rendering

⸻

⚙️ Why your brain does this

Because over-rendering = danger.

If your brain made everything vivid and certain:
	•	you’d mistake guesses for reality
	•	you’d act on false confidence

So instead it does:

low certainty → low resolution → low commitment
high certainty → high resolution → high commitment

That’s not a bug.

That’s a safety + efficiency system.

